# Phase 5 — Two-Layer Memory Verification

This screenshot was captured after Phase 5 end-to-end verification, when
the LangGraph reasoning agent had begun consuming pattern matches and
reifying its alerts back into Graphiti as a second layer of memory.

At capture time the system had produced:
- 8 contextual alerts emitted to the Kafka alerts topic
- 7 agent_alert episodes reified into Graphiti
- 8 training records written to JSONL for the downstream training pipeline
- Validation gate active: 3 of 8 records had confidence downgraded
  (raw mean 0.83 → final mean 0.79)
- All alerts grounded in ≥3 specific anchors quoted from retrieved
  historical episodes

## machine03_with_alerts.png

Memory graph for Machine-03 showing both episode types coexisting around
the same physical machine:

- ThermalVibrationCascade episodes — Layer 1 (facts detected by CEP)
- AgentAlert episodes — Layer 2 (interpretations produced by the agent's
  reasoning, reified back into the graph as new memory)

This is the architectural claim of HarmonicMesh rendered as a single
image: memory has two layers, and both layers connect to the same
physical entity they describe.

Cypher query used:

```cypher
MATCH (m:Machine {name: "Machine-03"})<-[r:MENTIONS]-(e:Episodic)
WHERE e.source_description IN ["HarmonicMesh CEP pattern match",
                                "HarmonicMesh agent alert"]
RETURN m, e, r
LIMIT 30
```

The agent's own prior alerts become retrievable context for future
reasoning cycles. During the test run, the agent successfully retrieved
one of its own earlier alerts and cited it as evidence in a subsequent
cascade — the Layer 2 memory feedback loop working in practice.